Przykad potoku przetwarzania

# From https://github.com/wlandau/drake-examples/
random_rows <- function(data, n) {
  data[sample.int(n = nrow(data), size = n, replace = TRUE), ]
}

simulate <- function(n) {
  data <- random_rows(data = mtcars, n = n)
  data.frame(x = data$wt, y = data$mpg)
}

reg1 <- function(d) {
  lm(y ~ + x, data = d)
}

reg2 <- function(d) {
  d$x2 <- d$x ^ 2
  lm(y ~ x2, data = d)
}

Przetwarzanie z uyciem pakietu drake

# From https://github.com/wlandau/drake-examples/
plan <- drake_plan(
  small = simulate(48), large = simulate(64),
  regression1 = target(
    reg1(data), transform = map(data = c(small, large), .tag_out = reg)
  ),
  regression2 = target(
    reg2(data), transform = map(data, .tag_out = reg)
  ),
  summ = target(
    suppressWarnings(summary(reg$residuals)),
    transform = map(reg)
  ),
  coef = target(
    suppressWarnings(summary(reg))$coefficients,
    transform = map(reg)
  )
)

Wizualizacja planu

# From https://github.com/wlandau/drake-examples/
config <- drake_config(plan)
drake_ggraph(config)

## Zbudowanie projektu

# From https://github.com/wlandau/drake-examples/
config <- drake_config(plan)
make(plan)
## All targets are already up to date.
drake_ggraph(config)

## Podsumowanie

  • Pozwala na zaoszczdzenie duej iloci czasu
  • Wymaga zmiany przyzwyczaje programisty
  • Sprzyja powtarzalnoci wynikw
  • atwe rozszerzenie o przetwarzanie rozproszone
